      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "aabd95c6-b65b-402a-b4ca-b21c19454e6d",
        "text": "IIT addresses the mind-body problem ([[Mind–body problem]]) by proposing an identity between phenomenological properties of experience and causal properties of physical systems: ''The conceptual structure specified by a complex of elements in a state is identical to its experience.''"
      },
      "after": "e2c17b62-13b5-4c7c-ae9a-e8cae7612506",
      "id": "aabd95c6-b65b-402a-b4ca-b21c19454e6d",
      "date": 1466433581699
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ff153467-fb06-42af-99af-8aedd4dd2b62",
        "text": "In this way, a conceptual structure <math>C</math> can be plotted as a '''constellation''' of points in cause-effect space. Each point is called a '''star''', and each star's magnitude (<math>\\varphi^{\\textrm{Max}}</math>) is its '''size'''."
      },
      "after": "aabd95c6-b65b-402a-b4ca-b21c19454e6d",
      "id": "ff153467-fb06-42af-99af-8aedd4dd2b62",
      "date": 1466433583520
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5dc61cf5-fc0c-4fac-8ac1-22f869475afd",
        "text": "Specifically, the form of the conceptual structure in cause-effect space completely specifies the quality of the experience, while the irreducibility <math>\\Phi^{\\textrm{Max}} </math> of the conceptual structure specifies the level to which it exists (i.e., the complex's level of consciousness).  The maximally irreducible cause-effect repertoire of each concept within a conceptual structure specifies what the concept contributes to the quality of the experience, while its irreducibility <math>\\varphi^{\\textrm{Max}} </math> specifies how much the concept is present in the experience."
      },
