      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "441b4320-de08-4b10-b3f7-70af87a16a21",
      "text": "# Mathematics: formalization of the postulates"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cc14815c-5c88-46aa-9e95-0050d858d90d",
      "text": "For a complete and thorough account of the mathematical formalization of IIT, see.<ref name=\":2\" /> What follows is intended as a brief summary, adapted from,[ ] of the most important quantities involved. Pseudocode for the algorithms used to calculate these quantities can be found at.[ ]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5eba1841-1a54-4719-b3b9-59e9ec7f09e0",
      "text": "# Cause-effect space"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "17e7ce3a-0551-4f72-a35a-9c2edd6c666d",
      "text": "For a system of N simple binary elements, '''cause-effect space''' is formed by 2\\times2^N axes, one for each possible past and future state of the system. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ef5f5a768111195c",
      "text": "Any cause-effect repertoire R, which specifies the probability of each possible past and future state of the system, can be easily plotted as a point in this high-dimensional space: The position of this point along each axis is given by the probability of that state as specified by <math>R</math>. If a point is also taken to have a scalar magnitude (which can be informally thought of as the point's \"size\", for example), then it can easily represent a concept: The concept's cause-effect repertoire specifies the location of the point in cause-effect space, and the concept's <math>\\varphi^{\\textrm{Max}}</math> value specifies that point's magnitude."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5dc61cf5-fc0c-4fac-8ac1-22f869475afd",
      "text": "Specifically, the form of the conceptual structure in cause-effect space completely specifies the quality of the experience, while the irreducibility <math>\\Phi^{\\textrm{Max}} </math> of the conceptual structure specifies the level to which it exists (i.e., the complex's level of consciousness).  The maximally irreducible cause-effect repertoire of each concept within a conceptual structure specifies what the concept contributes to the quality of the experience, while its irreducibility <math>\\varphi^{\\textrm{Max}} </math> specifies how much the concept is present in the experience."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e2c17b62-13b5-4c7c-ae9a-e8cae7612506",
      "text": "# Central Identity"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aabd95c6-b65b-402a-b4ca-b21c19454e6d",
      "text": "IIT addresses the mind-body problem ([[Mind–body problem]]) by proposing an identity between phenomenological properties of experience and causal properties of physical systems: ''The conceptual structure specified by a complex of elements in a state is identical to its experience.''"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ff153467-fb06-42af-99af-8aedd4dd2b62",
      "text": "In this way, a conceptual structure <math>C</math> can be plotted as a '''constellation''' of points in cause-effect space. Each point is called a '''star''', and each star's magnitude (<math>\\varphi^{\\textrm{Max}}</math>) is its '''size'''."
